<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910315-0075</DOCNO><DOCID>910315-0075.</DOCID><HL>   Law:   Justice Agency Sets Review   Of Police-Brutality Cases</HL><DATE>03/15/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3</SO><IN>LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)CONGRESS (CNG)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said thatin response to allegations of police brutality in LosAngeles, the U.S. Justice Department will review all&quot;official complaints&quot; of police brutality over the past sixyears.   Mr. Thornburgh announced the review after meeting withblack Reps. John Conyers (D., Mich.) and Edolphus Towns (D.,N.Y.). The Congressional Black Caucus had complained that therecent, highly publicized beating of a black man by LosAngeles police represents a nationwide problem of raciallyoriented police abuse.</LP><TEXT>   The attorney general didn't acknowledge any such nationalproblem. He said the purpose of the six-year review of policebrutality cases investigated by the Federal Bureau ofInvestigation is designed &quot;to discern whether any pattern ofmisconduct is apparent.&quot; The review doesn't focus on LosAngeles or on any other city, according to Justice Departmentofficials.   &quot;Responsible law-enforcement officers condemn acts ofpolice brutality by anyone in law enforcement,&quot; Mr.Thornburgh said. He said that over the past three years,federal prosecutors have brought criminal charges against 98people in police-misconduct cases. Of the 60 defendants whohave gone to trial so far, 45 have been convicted. Mr.Thornburgh hailed the 75% conviction rate in what he called&quot;difficult cases to obtain convictions.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>